[normal]Written evidence from the 
[normal]Airport Operators Association 
[normal](WRT 036)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Airport Operators Association (AOA) is the national voice of UK airports. We are a trade association representing the interests of UK airports, and the principal such body engaging with the UK Government and regulatory authorities on airport matters. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In recent years, UK airports have taken significant steps – and made major investments in specialist snow clearing equipment – to improve winter resilience. For example, Manchester Airport has invested around £6 million, Aberdeen £1.3 million and Heathrow
[normal] £32.4 million on new snow fleet equipment and staff. An AOA Snow Planning Survey, conducted in 
[normal]winter
[normal] 2012, shows good practice around UK airports, and is co-signed by AOA and the British Air Transport Association, the trade
[normal] body of UK airlines, which is 
[normal]enclosed below. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We would therefore advise that AOA member airports have a high state of preparedness for the forthcoming winter period. While it is almost inevitable that very severe winter weather will cause disruption to all modes of transport, UK airp
[normal]orts have:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition to the above, you may also wish to note that CAA led a trial during the last 
[normal]winter period concerned with the reporting of runway condition during winter conditions which involved both airports and airlines. Industry is currently awaiting the publication of the results of this trial but we believe that this further demonstrates our
[normal] desire to continually improve our overall winter resilience.
