[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]AIRPORT OPERATORS ASSOCIATION[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2012 SNOW PLANNING SURVEY[bold]&#xa0;[bold]SUMMARY OF FINDINGS[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]The UK in recent years has seen increased interest
[normal] by a number of stakeholders
[normal] in the issue of how civil aviation 
[normal]copes 
[normal]with the disruption 
[normal]exceptional weather events can cause. Such exceptional events – such as snow – can impact airports, airlines, surface access transport to airports; and ultimately this affects aviation personnel, freight operations and
[normal], of course,
[normal] passengers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 
[normal]early 
[normal]201
[normal]2, the CAA asked the aviation sector to produce a brief report which details the work UK aviation conducts to address exceptional weather events like snow. 
[normal]In response, o
[normal]n behalf of the UK airports sector
[normal],
[normal] the Airport Operators Association 
[normal](AOA) 
[normal]has liaise
[normal]d with 
[normal]a number of 
[normal]its network of members to produce the following overview of the positive steps taken by airports in readiness for winter operations.
[normal] In producing the report, AOA has worked with the British Air Transport Association (BATA) and several of
[normal] its member airlines to ensure the findings reflect efforts made not only by airport operators but also by UK airlines. Other stakeholders – including national and local government and their agencies – also have key roles to play in ensuring airport and ai
[normal]rline operations can continue to function during challenging winter weather conditions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Please see in the pages to follow a
[normal] list of examples of the work airports 
[normal]and airlines undertake 
[normal]to address snow events which can affect their winter operations. When 
[normal]reading this document, it is important to bear in mind that there should be no expectation that these activities are being done by all airports or 
[normal]airlines or 
[normal]indeed are appropriate for all airports 
[normal]and airlines 
[normal]– the list merely highlights the work and in
[normal]itiatives undertaken to deal with 
[normal]adverse winter weather
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The document details examples of recent changes and good practice conducted by UK airports and airlines in three sections: operational; management; and passenger communications and welfare. Its 
[normal]purpose is to provide an indicative précis of some of the work UK airports and airlines perform where appropriate t to address the impact of snow on winter operations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We thank the following airports for their assistance: Aberdeen, Belfast City, Birmingha
[normal]m, Blackpool, Bristol, Edinburgh, Exeter, Gatwick, Glasgow, Heathrow, Leeds Bradford, Liverpool, London City, Luton, Manchester, Newcastle, Newquay Cornwall, Norwich, Prestwick, Southampton, and Stansted.
